Analysis summary

- Endpoint path (with correct prefix): /api/v0/lifecycle/configure
  - Rationale: Class is annotated with @Path("/api/v0/lifecycle") and the two methods handling configuration are both @Path("/configure") and @POST, giving the full path /api/v0/lifecycle/configure. There are two POST methods at this path (one JSON, one YAML).

- All HTTP methods acceptable: false
  - Rationale: Only POST is implemented for /configure. There are no methods annotated for other HTTP verbs on this path.

- HEAD acceptable: false
  - Rationale: There is no method annotated with HEAD for this path, and the code does not provide a HEAD handler for /api/v0/lifecycle/configure.

- POST acceptable: true
  - Rationale: There are two POST methods for /api/v0/lifecycle/configure:
    - configureNodeJson at /configure consuming application/json
    - configureNode at /configure consuming application/yaml or text/yaml (hidden)
  - Both implement the endpoint logic for configuring Cassandra/DSE.

- OPTIONS acceptable: false
  - Rationale: There is no explicit @OPTIONS handler in the code for this path. Based solely on the code, OPTIONS is not defined.

- TRACE acceptable: false
  - Rationale: No TRACE handler present in code for this path.

- GET acceptable: false
  - Rationale: No GET handler for /api/v0/lifecycle/configure in the code.

- PUT acceptable: false
  - Rationale: No PUT handler for /api/v0/lifecycle/configure in the code.

- DELETE acceptable: false
  - Rationale: No DELETE handler for /api/v0/lifecycle/configure in the code.

- PATCH acceptable: false
  - Rationale: No PATCH handler for /api/v0/lifecycle/configure in the code.

Explanation

- The only HTTP methods implemented for the /api/v0/lifecycle/configure path are POST (two variants: one JSON, one YAML). This makes POST the sole acceptable method for this endpoint.
- There are no methods annotated for HEAD, GET, PUT, DELETE, PATCH, or OPTIONS on /api/v0/lifecycle/configure, so those are not considered acceptable based on the code.
- The two POST methods exist to support different content types (application/json and application/yaml/text/yaml). One is tagged @Hidden to suppress OpenAPI generation, but it still participates in handling POST requests to the same path.
- The path itself has no dynamic path parameters, so it remains /api/v0/lifecycle/configure with no {param} placeholders.
